{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a565d04f-936f-4581-a664-d9cd1f034d66","content":"Here's how to connect your C# MCP server to the **MCP Inspector**:\n\n### 1. Run the Inspector\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\n\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:6274`).\n\n### 2. Configure the connection\n\nIn the Inspector UI:\n\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourMcpServer.csproj`\n\nOr if you have a built DLL:\n\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `/path/to/YourMcpServer.dll`\n\nThen click **Connect**.\n\n### 3. Debug\n\nOnce connected, the Inspector lets you:\n\n- **List Tools** — verify your tools are registered\n- **Call Tools** — send requests with sample inputs and see responses\n- **View Logs** — inspect the raw JSON-RPC messages over stdio\n\n### Tips\n\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** and reads from **stdin**. Any logging should go to **stderr** (not stdout), or it will corrupt the protocol stream.\n- If you use `Console.WriteLine` for debugging, switch to `Console.Error.WriteLine` instead.\n- You can pass environment variables in the Inspector UI if your server needs them (e.g., API keys).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"af4544de-a2dd-4d50-9b89-7b3537d9b511","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to connect a C# MCP server (using stdio transport) to the MCP Inspector for interactive testing/debugging. This is a knowledge question — I can answer directly without needing to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":384},"id":"48158fab-dd12-41df-be6a-b137440508fb","timestamp":"2026-04-05T00:53:16.216Z","parentId":"3788e1a5-5943-4e01-bc06-4af05a76948e"}
